        <h1>Shuvansh Mental Health and Rehabilitation Hub</h1>
        <p class="tagline">Groups patients into compatible therapy clusters and suggests therapy-group assignments using clustering and matching techniques.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- DESCRIPTION -->
    <div class="description-box">
        <h2>üìã What is Shuvansh?</h2>
        <p>
            Shuvansh is a mental health & rehabilitation platform that groups patients into compatible therapy clusters based on clinical features,
            symptom scores, therapy goals, availability, and social compatibility. The hub helps clinicians form therapy groups (support groups, CBT groups,
            rehab cohorts) that maximize therapeutic compatibility and safety while respecting constraints such as language, severity, comorbidities, and clinician capacity.
        </p>
        <p><b>Core capabilities:</b> patient feature engineering, dimensionality reduction, cluster discovery (K-Means baseline), constrained cluster assignment, cluster validation, and therapist-group matching.</p>

        <div class="metrics-grid">
            <div class="metric-card"><div class="metric-value">85%</div><div class="metric-label">Avg within-cluster similarity</div></div>
            <div class="metric-card"><div class="metric-value">12</div><div class="metric-label">Avg group size</div></div>
            <div class="metric-card"><div class="metric-value">4</div><div class="metric-label">Therapy modalities supported</div></div>
            <div class="metric-card"><div class="metric-value">75%</div><div class="metric-label">Improved adherence (pilot)</div></div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- SDG ALIGNMENT -->
    <div class="sdg-box">
        <h3>üåç UN SDG Alignment (relevant SDG numbers)</h3>
        <div style="display:flex; gap:12px; flex-wrap:wrap; margin-top:8px;">
            <span class="badge">SDG 3</span>
            <span class="badge">SDG 4</span>
            <span class="badge">SDG 10</span>
            <span class="badge">SDG 8</span>
        </div>
        <p style="margin-top:10px;">
            <b>Why:</b> Shuvansh supports Good Health & Well-being (SDG 3) through improved therapy outcomes, Quality Education (SDG 4) via clinician upskilling,
            Reduced Inequalities (SDG 10) by targeting underserved groups, and Decent Work (SDG 8) by enabling more effective clinician workflows.
        </p>
    </div>

    <!-- PROBLEM -->
    <h2>üéØ Problem</h2>
    <div class="section-box problem-box">
        <p>
            Given N patients with feature vectors (clinical scores, demographics, language, therapy goals, availability), partition them into therapy groups so that:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>Patients in the same group are clinically compatible (high similarity)</li>
            <li>Group sizes follow min/max bounds (safety and effectiveness)</li>
            <li>Constraints like language, severity thresholds, clinician expertise are respected</li>
            <li>Assignments are robust and explainable to clinicians</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- SOLUTION OVERVIEW -->
    <h2>üí° Solution Overview</h2>
    <div class="section-box solution-box">
        <p>Pipeline (typical):</p>
        <ol>
            <li>Data preprocessing & feature engineering (normalize clinical scales, encode categorical features, privacy-preserving steps)</li>
            <li>Dimensionality reduction: <b>PCA</b> for visualization and noise reduction</li>
            <li>Clustering: <b>K-Means</b> as the baseline clustering method</li>
            <li>Cluster validation: silhouette, Davies‚ÄìBouldin index, clinical review</li>
            <li>Constrained assignment / matching to therapists: bipartite matching or min-cost max-flow to respect clinician capacity and preferences</li>
            <li>Refinement: local search to adjust clusters under constraints</li>
        </ol>
    </div>

    <!-- K-MEANS DETAILS -->
    <div class="algo-section">
        <h2>üîé K-Means Clustering (Baseline)</h2>

        <div class="code-box">
K-MEANS(P, k)
INPUT: P = {p1...pN} patient feature vectors, k = desired number of clusters
OUTPUT: cluster assignment C[i] for each patient

1. Initialize k centroids (randomly or k-means++)
2. repeat
3.   for each patient p:
4.     assign p to nearest centroid (by Euclidean / chosen distance)
5.   for each centroid j:
6.     update centroid = mean of points assigned to j
7. until assignments do not change or max iterations reached
8. return assignments
        </div>

        <button class="btn" onclick="toggleCode('py-skel')">Show Python skeleton (pipeline)</button>

        <div id="py-skel" class="py-code">
# Python-like skeleton for Shuvansh pipeline (runnable after filling procedures)
import numpy as np
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score

# 1. build features
X, meta = build_features(patient_records)   # X: N x D

# 2. normalize + reduce
X = StandardScaler().fit_transform(X)
X_red = PCA(n_components=10).fit_transform(X)

# 3. baseline clustering
k = choose_k(X_red)  # e.g., elbow or clinician input
km = KMeans(n_clusters=k, init='k-means++', n_init=10)
labels = km.fit_predict(X_red)
score = silhouette_score(X_red, labels)

# 4. constrained clustering or local repair if constraints exist
# 5. summarize clusters and match to therapists (min-cost flow)
        </div>

        <div class="section-box datastructure-box">
            <h3>üóÑ Data & Matching</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><b>Feature matrix:</b> numeric clinical features (normalized)</li>
                <li><b>Cluster summaries:</b> representative statistics per cluster for clinician review</li>
                <li><b>Matching:</b> bipartite graph between clusters/patients and therapists (min-cost max-flow)</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="section-box complexity-box">
            <h3>‚è± Complexity & Practical Notes</h3>
            <p><b>K-Means:</b> O(N ¬∑ k ¬∑ iters ¬∑ d) per run. Use k-means++ and multiple inits. Interpretability: provide cluster centroids and representative patients.</p>
            <p><b>Matching:</b> Min-cost flow complexity depends on the solver; practical sizes require efficient libraries (OR-Tools, network simplex).</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- DATA & ETHICS -->
    <h2>üßæ Data, Ethics & Safety</h2>
    <div class="section-box notes-box">
        <ul>
            <li>All patient data must be anonymized/pseudonymized; follow applicable health-data regulations (e.g., HIPAA, GDPR).</li>
            <li>Clinician-in-the-loop: automatic clusters are recommendations ‚Äî final grouping must be reviewed by clinicians.</li>
            <li>Bias checks: ensure features do not encode unfair proxies (race, socioeconomic status) unless clinically justified and explicitly consented.</li>
            <li>Explainability: provide cluster summaries (top features, representative patient profiles) for clinician trust.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- TECH STACK & METRICS -->
    <h2>üß∞ Tech Stack & Key Metrics</h2>
    <div class="section-box">
